No, apparently not. The creature just snarled and tried to fly directly toward Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry as she nearly lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
" HOW CAN WE KILL HER? ", screamed Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!"
"THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin sneezed and then drew a circle closer to the mountain that he called his home. The dark beast followed, but quickly fell into panic when a fiery ray struck her from behind. She hadn't noticed that she was no longer alone. She became even more panicked as Thassalin slowed down and then hurled his tail at her head, knocking her off course.
Snarling and growling, she flew upward and spat into the air. Everything suddenly turned dark, as if the monster had sucked the light from the sky into itself and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly could no longer see anything, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree canopy before finally crashing into an open clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and it rushed directly toward him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!" shouted Tenuk as he slipped out of the cloud and began circling, scanning the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What are we supposed to do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi painfully got to her feet. She was certain she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already beginning to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhaustedly against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to reach Thassalin's side, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch-black, shrouded in eerie shadows. And within this darkness, something screamed and screeched.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed down beside Nyssi onto the ground, knocking her to the earth. However, she noticed that the tail was merely swinging wildly and not deliberately trying to hit her. The beast—or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it—growled and slashed at the shadows it had created with its claws. Something shot through the darkness, lunged at the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a gunshot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground, and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissipated, and they saw what had happened: standing on top of the beast was Kayel, holding his rifle with heavy, labored breathing.
"That was probably… the craziest shadow leap I've ever made… Thanto kat'olon…," Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy circled his body. But as he was still speaking, color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow hue.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, because most people found them eerie and quite frightening. But Nyssi had not known that Kayel could use these powers in any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was acting suggested that he was clearly quite surprised as well.
"Are you okay?" came out of Nyssi.
" Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be alright again soon." Kayel looked at his work, while Tenuk descended, landed beside him, and once again assumed his normal spastic form.
Now that the beast was no longer moving, they could see more clearly what it was. Its skin was black as ravens and slimy, but the slime remained stuck to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns stood out from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask themselves what the hell they were facing, something screamed and leaped out from a nearby bush. It didn't reach them, however, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, causing the creature to slide to a halt at Nyssi's feet. Nyssi wanted to take no risks. She grabbed her shot gun, fired without thinking at its head, and the creature died right there.
"Ups..." muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and stepping out of the truck. "Uh, that wasn't really intentional. Are you all okay?"
"Tenuk scolded, 'You missed the whole action,' 'Where were you?'"
„You all just left me standing there. I came as quickly as I could…“, sighed Retvik. „May I ask, what terrible creatures those are?“
Rettvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had recovered somewhat. He was covered in cuts and scrapes and seemed a bit dazed, but not seriously injured.
"You have killed the corrupt ones! The infected monsters. Beings that are leaving here, as the corruption attacked your gods."
" Do you mean that terrible god-monster thing that we... helped kill?" stuttered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR IS IT?" Thassalin hobbled over to Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO SKILLED IN KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES."
"Er... thank you... I think," Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few pictures of the now definitely dead creatures. Then she pulled out her favorite weapon, the ornate death god dagger, and began sawing off one of the creature's horns. Next, she moved on to the second one. But just as Nyssi finished, the creatures suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes in an instant. The same thing happened to the horns she had cut off.
"So, that's both practical and impractical at the same time…", sighed Nyssi. "But at least I have the photos, I hope."
